)\n* [[Pine Air, Florida|Pine Air]]\n* [[Plantation Mobile Home Park, Florida|Plantation Mobile Home Park]] (s)\n* [[Royal Palm Estates, Florida|Royal Palm Estates]] (n)\n* [[San Castle, Florida|San Castle]]\n* [[Schall Circle, Florida|Schall Circle]] (v)\n* [[Seminole Manor, Florida|Seminole Manor]] (j)\n* [[Stacy Street, Florida|Stacey Street]] (q)\n* [[The Acreage, Florida|The Acreage]]\n* [[Watergate, Florida|Watergate]]\n* [[Westgate, Florida|Westgate]] (t)\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Former census-designated places===\nSeveral unincorporated parts of Palm Beach County were listed as census-designated places for the [[2000 United States Census|2000 census]], but were not listed for the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]]:\n{{div col|colwidth=15em}}\n* [[Belle Glade Camp, Florida|Belle Glade Camp]] (l)\n* [[Boca Del Mar, Florida|Boca Del Mar]] (c)\n* [[Boca Pointe, Florida|Boca Pointe]] (a)\n* [[Cypress Lakes, Florida|Cypress Lakes]] (w)\n* [[Dunes Road, Florida|Dunes Road]] (cc)\n* [[Fremd Village-Padgett Island, Florida|Fremd Village-Padgett Island]] (aa)\n* [[Golden Lakes, Florida|Golden Lakes]] (r)\n* [[Hamptons at Boca Raton, Florida|Hamptons at Boca Raton]] (e)\n* [[High Point, Palm Beach County, Florida|High Point]] (i)\n* [[Kings Point, Florida|Kings Point]] (g)\n* [[Lakewood Gardens, Florida|Lakewood Gardens]]\n* [[Lake Worth Corridor, Florida|Lake Worth Corridor]] (k)\n* [[Lakeside Green, Florida|Lakeside Green]] (x)\n* [[Mission Bay, Florida|Mission Bay]] (d)\n* [[Sandalfoot Cove, Florida|Sandalfoot Cove]] (b)\n* [[Villages of Oriole, Florida|Villages of Oriole]] (h)\n* [[Whisper Walk, Florida|Whisper Walk]] (f)\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Other unincorporated area===\n* [[Century Village, Florida|Century Village]] (u)\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Palm Beach County, Florida]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n<!---most of these government links need to be moved about into a \"government\" subsection with some explanation--->\n\n===Government links/Constitutional offices===\n* [http://www.co.palm-beach.fl.us/ Palm Beach County Government / Board of County Commissioners] official website\n* [http://www.pbcelections.org/ Palm Beach County Supervisor of Elections]\n* [http://www.co.palm-beach.fl.us/papa/ Palm Beach County Property Appraiser]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070321160141/http://www.pbcgov.com/tax/ Palm Beach County Tax Collector]\n* [http://www.pbso.org/ Palm Beach County Sheriff's Office]\n* [http://www.mypalmbeachclerk.com/ Clerk & Comptroller, Palm Beach County]\n\n====Special districts====\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071110195356/http://www.palmbeach.k12.fl.us/ Palm Beach County School District]\n* [https://www.pbswcd.org/ Soil and Water Conservation District]\n* [http://www.sfwmd.gov South Florida Water Management]\n\n====Emergency services====\n* [http://www.pbso.org Palm Beach County Sheriff's Office]\n* [[Palm Beach County Fire-Rescue]]\n\n====Judicial branch====\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070204125619/http://www.co.palm-beach.fl.us/opd/ Palm Beach County Public Defender]\n* [http://www.sa15.state.fl.us/ Palm Beach County State Attorney's Office, 15th Judicial Circuit]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070302164045/http://www.co.palm-beach.fl.us/cadmin/ 15th Judicial Circuit of Florida]\n\n===Tourism links===\n* [http://www.palmbeachfl.com/ Palm Beach County Convention and Visitors Bureau]\n* [http://www.palmbeaches.org/ Chamber of Commerce of the Palm Beaches]\n\n{{Coord|26.71|-80.05|type:city_region:US|format=dms|display=title}}\n\n{{Geographic location\n|Centre = Palm Beach County, Florida\n|North = [[Martin County, Florida|Martin County]]\n|Northeast =\n|East = [[Atlantic Ocean]]\n|Southeast =\n|South = [[Broward County, Florida|Broward County]]\n|Southwest =\n|West = [[Hendry County, Florida|Hendry County]]\n|Northwest = [[Okeechobee County, Florida|Okeechobee County]] and [[Glades County, Florida|Glades County]]\n}}\n\n{{Palm Beach County, Florida}}\n{{Miami metropolitan area}}\n{{Greater Miami}}\n{{Florida}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Counties in the Miami metropolitan area]]\n[[Category:Charter counties in Florida]]\n[[Category:Palm Beach County, Florida| ]]\n[[Category:1909 establishments in Florida]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1909]]\n", "name_user": "Whoisjohngalt", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleaned up usingAutoEd", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Palm_Beach_County,_Florida"}
{"title_page": "1946 Cook County, Illinois elections", "text_new": "{{Short description|American elections}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Elections in Illinois}}\n{{Richard J. Daley series}}\nElections were held in [[Cook County, Illinois]], on November 5, 1946. [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]s took control of most county offices and occupied both seats of the Board of Appeals,<ref name=\"Arlington Heights Herald\">{{cite news |title=Democrats save only three county offices |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/45900714/democrats-save-only-three-county-offices/ |accessdate=1 March 2020 |work=Arlington Heights Herald |volume=20 |issue=11 |page=1 |date=November 8, 1946 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> although [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]]s retained their majority in the [[Cook County Board of Commissioners|Board of Commissioners]].<ref name=\"Continued majority\">{{cite news |title=Democrats put 208 employes[sic] in job shelter |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/45900332/democrats-put-208-employees-in-job/ |accessdate=1 March 2020 |work=Chicago Tribune |volume=105 |issue=281 |page=14 |date=November 23, 1946 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> The Republican landslide reflected similar trends in state and federal elections at the time but was nevertheless unexpected. It resulted in the resignation of Democratic leader [[Edward Joseph Kelly]] and ultimately the end of his tenure as [[Mayor of Chicago]]. Republicans failed to capitalize on this victory in the following year's Chicago mayoral election, which was won by Democrat Martin Kennelly.\n\nDemocrat [[Richard J. Daley]] was defeated for the position of Sheriff by Republican candidate Elmer Michael Walsh.<ref name=\"Arlington Heights Herald\"/> This would be the only loss of his career; he later became the Chairman of the [[Cook County Democratic Party]] Central Committee and served as Mayor of Chicago from 1955 to 1976, while Walsh would die in obscurity.\n\n==Background==\n[[Patrick Nash]], who had constructed a powerful [[political machine]] with [[Anton Cermak]] and served as Democratic party chairman since 1931, died in 1943.{{sfn|Royko|p=54|ps=none}} [[Edward Joseph Kelly]], who had been Mayor of Chicago since Cermak's inadvertent{{efn|Cermak died from gunshot wounds intended for U.S. President-elect [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]].{{sfn|Royko|p=42|ps=none}} Some claim that Cermak was the intended target, but this is generally discounted among historians.}} assassination in 1933,{{sfn|Royko|p=42|ps=none}} assumed the chair.{{sfn|Royko|p=54|ps=none}} Kelly was an inadequate leader of both the party and municipal government,{{sfn|Royko|p=54|ps=none}} and received criticism for poor delivery of city services and allowing political appointments in the public school administration.{{sfn|Royko|p=55|ps=none}} Nevertheless, Democrats had been largely unopposed in the 1944 elections.<ref name=\"Tribune primary\"/>\n\nOffices that were contested included the Treasurer, Assessor, Sheriff, County Clerk, County Superintendent of Public Schools, County Judge, Judge and Clerk of the Probate Court, and the Clerk of the Criminal Court,<ref name=\"Arlington Heights Herald\"/><ref name=\"Herald\">{{cite news |title=Announce final election results |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/45929086/announce-final-election-results/ |accessdate=1 March 2020 |work=Arlington Heights Herald |volume=20 |issue=14 |page=1 |date=November 29, 1946 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> as well as the President of the Board of Commissioners, both members of the Board of Appeals, and the other members of the Board of Commissioners.<ref name=\"Arlington Heights Herald\"/> Excluding the President, 15 people were elected to the Board of Commissioners; ten representatives from the city of Chicago and five from the rest of the county.<ref name=\"Encyclopedia\">{{cite encyclopedia |work=The Electronic Encyclopedia of Chicago |title=Cook County |date=2005 |publisher=Chicago Historical Society |last=Keating |first=Ann Durkin |url=http://www.encyclopedia.chicagohistory.org/pages/335.html |access-date=March 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Primary elections==\nPrimary elections were held on April 9.<ref name=\"Tribune primary\">{{cite news |title=Primary called merely a drill for November |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/371993923/ |url-access=subscription |accessdate=1 March 2020 |work=Chicago Tribune |volume=105 |issue=84 |page=13 |date=April 8, 1946 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> The primaries of both parties were generally considered uncompetitive.<ref name=\"Tribune primary\"/> These were the first primaries in Illinois after [[World War II]]; both parties sought to include veterans on their tickets.<ref name=\"Tribune primary\"/> Leaders of both parties exhorted supporters to attend the primaries.<ref name=\"Tribune primary\"/>\n\n===Democratic primaries===\nRichard J. Daley, Cook County Comptroller and a [[Illinois Senate|state senator]] who dealt with legislation related to Chicago on Kelly's behalf,{{sfn|Royko|p=53|ps=none}} ran for the Democratic nomination for Sheriff.{{sfn|Royko|p=54|ps=none}} This came as a surprise to some given Daley's reputation for integrity and the notoriety of the Sheriff's office for improper collections of money from motorists and suburban adult establishments.{{sfn|Royko|p=54|ps=none}} The position was term-limited to one term, and most officeholders used the opportunity to collect money.{{sfn|Royko|p=54|ps=none}} Daley had never previously run for office outside of his Senate district, and appealed to Kelly for his relative obscurity and lack of previous scandals, something which was uncommon among Democrats of the time.{{sfn|Royko|p=54|ps=none}}\n\n===Republican primaries===\n[[Evanston Township, Cook County, Illinois|Evanston Township]] had an unexpected three-way contest for Republican party committeeman, with incumbent Alan E. Ashcraft Jr. being challenged by [[Evanston, Illinois|Evanston]] alderman Robert E. James and Benjamin F. E. Ricker.<ref name=\"Tribune primary\"/> Ashcraft survived the challenge and was named Vice President of the Republican Country Towns Organization of Cook County in May.<ref name=\"Ashcraft\">{{cite news |last1=Tagge |first1=George |title=Country Group Elects |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/45934430/country-group-elects/ |accessdate=1 March 2020 |work=Chicago Tribune |volume=105 |issue=112 |page=3 |date=May 10, 1946 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\n==General election==\nThe general election was held on November 5.<ref name=\"Arlington Heights Herald\"/> Harriet M. Robinson, the president of the Honest Ballot Committee, called for the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] to investigate the election on October 20, accusing the Board of Election commissioners of delaying the release of precinct voter registers.<ref name=\"FBI\">{{cite news |title=Ballot list fraud is charged; probe by FBI demanded |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/45899991/ballot-list-fraud-is-charges-probe-by/ |accessdate=1 March 2020 |work=Chicago Tribune |volume=105 |issue=252 |page=5 |date=October 21, 1946 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nThe results were a landslide for the GOP.<ref name=\"Arlington Heights Herald\"/> Only three Democrats\u2014Edmund K. Jarecki for County Court Judge, Michael J. Flynn for County Clerk, and John S. Clark for Assessor\u2014retained countywide office.<ref name=\"Arlington Heights Herald\"/> The results mirrored similar pro-Republican trends at the state and federal level but were unexpected by either party.<ref name=\"Arlington Heights Herald\"/>\n\n===Sheriff===\nDaley was the favorite to win the position of Sheriff.<ref name=\"Corman\"/> \"We were delighted that Dad was a candidate. Daley seemed almost impossible to beat, but it was an honor just to be named to run against him,\" recalled Walsh's son Elmer Jr.<ref name=\"Corman\"/> However, Daley suffered from the general tide against the Democrats while Walsh benefited from being a veteran of World War II.{{sfn|Royko|p=55|ps=none}}\n\n===Courts===\nJarecki, who had been the County Judge since 1922,<ref name=\"Jarecki\">{{cite web |last1=Bolek |first1=Francis |title=Jarecki, Edmund K. |url=http://www.poles.org/db/J_names/Jarecki_EK.html |publisher=Poles in America Foundation |accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref> had such a narrow margin of victory that it was possible that he might have lost as of November 8,<ref name=\"Arlington Heights Herald\"/> and ultimately had a margin of victory of only 8,873 votes in what was the closest election.<ref name=\"Herald\"/>\n\n[[File:Cook County Probate Judge 1946.png|thumb|Results of the probate judge election.]]\nRepublican candidate William Waugh won the Probate Court Judgeship, defeating the Democratic opponent John F. O'Connell.<ref name=\"Arlington Heights Herald\"/>\n\n==Aftermath and legacy==\nThe elections proved to be Kelly's downfall. [[Jacob Arvey]], a Democratic west side boss who had returned from the war, convinced him to resign as chairman.{{sfn|Royko|p=55|ps=none}} In the following year's [[1947 Chicago mayoral election|Chicago mayoral election]] Kelly was replaced by [[Martin Kennelly]] as the Democratic candidate.{{sfn|Royko|p=56|ps=none}}\n\nThe shrieval race would be Daley's only electoral defeat.<ref name=\"Corman\">{{cite news |last1=Corman |first1=Stephen |title=The man who defeated Richard J. Daley |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/45932373/the-man-who-defeated-richard-j-daley/ |accessdate=1 March 2020 |work=Chicago Tribune Magazine |issue=Section 9 |date=February 27, 1977 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Daley became the Chairman of the Cook County Democratic Party Central Committee in 1953 and the Mayor of Chicago in 1955,<ref name=\"Casey\"/> serving both positions until his death in 1976. Walsh served as Sheriff until 1950 but faded from relevance,<ref name=\"Casey\">{{cite news |last1=Casey |first1=Bob |title=Chicago and Mayor Daley the same |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/45930819/elk-grove-herald/ |accessdate=1 March 2020 |work=Elk Grove Herald |volume=18 |issue=267 Section 2 |page=1 |date=March 28, 1975 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> dying in 1962.<ref name=\"Corman\"/>\n\nThe Probate Court, Criminal Court, and County Court were abolished in 1964 upon the formation of the [[Circuit Court of Cook County]] to unify the courts of Cook County into a single jurisdiction. Countywide voting for the Board of Commissioners ended in 1994 when districts were established to elect each commissioner. The Board of Appeals was replaced by a three-member [[Cook County Board of Review|Board of Review]] in 1998.<ref name=\"Board of Review\">{{cite web |title=History of The Board of Review |url=https://cookcountyboardofreview.com/about/history-of-the-board-of-review |publisher=Cook County Board of Review |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Works cited==\n*{{cite book |last=Royko |first=Mike |author-link=Mike Royko |title=Boss: Richard J. Daley of Chicago |year=1971 |url=https://archive.org/details/bossrichardjdale00royk |publisher=Signet |location=New York, New York |ref={{harvid|Royko}}}}\n\n[[Category:Cook County, Illinois elections]]\n[[Category:1946 Illinois elections]]\n\n{{Illinois elections}}\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|American elections}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Elections in Illinois}}\n{{Richard J. Daley series}}\nElections were held in [[Cook County, Illinois]], on November 5, 1946. [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]s took control of most county offices and occupied both seats of the Board of Appeals,<ref name=\"Arlington Heights Herald\">{{cite news |title=Democrats save only three county offices |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/45900714/democrats-save-only-three-county-offices/ |accessdate=1 March 2020 |work=Arlington Heights Herald |volume=20 |issue=11 |page=1 |date=November 8, 1946 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> although [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]]s retained their majority in the [[Cook County Board of Commissioners|Board of Commissioners]].<ref name=\"Continued majority\">{{cite news |title=Democrats put 208 employes[sic] in job shelter |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/45900332/democrats-put-208-employees-in-job/ |accessdate=1 March 2020 |work=Chicago Tribune |volume=105 |issue=281 |page=14 |date=November 23, 1946 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> The Republican landslide reflected similar trends in state and federal elections at the time but was nevertheless unexpected. It resulted in the resignation of Democratic leader Edward Joseph Kelly and ultimately the end of his tenure as [[Mayor of Chicago]]. Republicans failed to capitalize on this victory in the following year's Chicago mayoral election, which was won by Democrat Martin Kennelly.\n\nDemocrat [[Richard J. Daley]] was defeated for the position of Sheriff by Republican candidate Elmer Michael Walsh.<ref name=\"Arlington Heights Herald\"/> This would be the only loss of his career; he later became the Chairman of the [[Cook County Democratic Party]] Central Committee and served as Mayor of Chicago from 1955 to 1976, while Walsh would die in obscurity.\n\n==Background==\n[[Patrick Nash]], who had constructed a powerful [[political machine]] with [[Anton Cermak]] and served as Democratic party chairman since 1931, died in 1943.{{sfn|Royko|p=54|ps=none}} [[Edward Joseph Kelly]], who had been Mayor of Chicago since Cermak's inadvertent{{efn|Cermak died from gunshot wounds intended for U.S. President-elect [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]].{{sfn|Royko|p=42|ps=none}} Some claim that Cermak was the intended target, but this is generally discounted among historians.}} assassination in 1933,{{sfn|Royko|p=42|ps=none}} assumed the chair.{{sfn|Royko|p=54|ps=none}} Kelly was an inadequate leader of both the party and municipal government,{{sfn|Royko|p=54|ps=none}} and received criticism for poor delivery of city services and allowing political appointments in the public school administration.{{sfn|Royko|p=55|ps=none}} Nevertheless, Democrats had been largely unopposed in the 1944 elections.<ref name=\"Tribune primary\"/>\n\nOffices that were contested included the Treasurer, Assessor, Sheriff, County Clerk, County Superintendent of Public Schools, County Judge, Judge and Clerk of the Probate Court, and the Clerk of the Criminal Court,<ref name=\"Arlington Heights Herald\"/><ref name=\"Herald\">{{cite news |title=Announce final election results |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/45929086/announce-final-election-results/ |accessdate=1 March 2020 |work=Arlington Heights Herald |volume=20 |issue=14 |page=1 |date=November 29, 1946 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> as well as the President of the Board of Commissioners, both members of the Board of Appeals, and the other members of the Board of Commissioners.<ref name=\"Arlington Heights Herald\"/> Excluding the President, 15 people were elected to the Board of Commissioners; ten representatives from the city of Chicago and five from the rest of the county.<ref name=\"Encyclopedia\">{{cite encyclopedia |work=The Electronic Encyclopedia of Chicago |title=Cook County |date=2005 |publisher=Chicago Historical Society |last=Keating |first=Ann Durkin |url=http://www.encyclopedia.chicagohistory.org/pages/335.html |access-date=March 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Primary elections==\nPrimary elections were held on April 9.<ref name=\"Tribune primary\">{{cite news |title=Primary called merely a drill for November |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/371993923/ |url-access=subscription |accessdate=1 March 2020 |work=Chicago Tribune |volume=105 |issue=84 |page=13 |date=April 8, 1946 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> The primaries of both parties were generally considered uncompetitive.<ref name=\"Tribune primary\"/> These were the first primaries in Illinois after [[World War II]]; both parties sought to include veterans on their tickets.<ref name=\"Tribune primary\"/> Leaders of both parties exhorted supporters to attend the primaries.<ref name=\"Tribune primary\"/>\n\n===Democratic primaries===\nRichard J. Daley, Cook County Comptroller and a [[Illinois Senate|state senator]] who dealt with legislation related to Chicago on Kelly's behalf,{{sfn|Royko|p=53|ps=none}} ran for the Democratic nomination for Sheriff.{{sfn|Royko|p=54|ps=none}} This came as a surprise to some given Daley's reputation for integrity and the notoriety of the Sheriff's office for improper collections of money from motorists and suburban adult establishments.{{sfn|Royko|p=54|ps=none}} The position was term-limited to one term, and most officeholders used the opportunity to collect money.{{sfn|Royko|p=54|ps=none}} Daley had never previously run for office outside of his Senate district, and appealed to Kelly for his relative obscurity and lack of previous scandals, something which was uncommon among Democrats of the time.{{sfn|Royko|p=54|ps=none}}\n\n===Republican primaries===\n[[Evanston Township, Cook County, Illinois|Evanston Township]] had an unexpected three-way contest for Republican party committeeman, with incumbent Alan E. Ashcraft Jr. being challenged by [[Evanston, Illinois|Evanston]] alderman Robert E. James and Benjamin F. E. Ricker.<ref name=\"Tribune primary\"/> Ashcraft survived the challenge and was named Vice President of the Republican Country Towns Organization of Cook County in May.<ref name=\"Ashcraft\">{{cite news |last1=Tagge |first1=George |title=Country Group Elects |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/45934430/country-group-elects/ |accessdate=1 March 2020 |work=Chicago Tribune |volume=105 |issue=112 |page=3 |date=May 10, 1946 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\n==General election==\nThe general election was held on November 5.<ref name=\"Arlington Heights Herald\"/> Harriet M. Robinson, the president of the Honest Ballot Committee, called for the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] to investigate the election on October 20, accusing the Board of Election commissioners of delaying the release of precinct voter registers.<ref name=\"FBI\">{{cite news |title=Ballot list fraud is charged; probe by FBI demanded |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/45899991/ballot-list-fraud-is-charges-probe-by/ |accessdate=1 March 2020 |work=Chicago Tribune |volume=105 |issue=252 |page=5 |date=October 21, 1946 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nThe results were a landslide for the GOP.<ref name=\"Arlington Heights Herald\"/> Only three Democrats\u2014Edmund K. Jarecki for County Court Judge, Michael J. Flynn for County Clerk, and John S. Clark for Assessor\u2014retained countywide office.<ref name=\"Arlington Heights Herald\"/> The results mirrored similar pro-Republican trends at the state and federal level but were unexpected by either party.<ref name=\"Arlington Heights Herald\"/>\n\n===Sheriff===\nDaley was the favorite to win the position of Sheriff.<ref name=\"Corman\"/> \"We were delighted that Dad was a candidate. Daley seemed almost impossible to beat, but it was an honor just to be named to run against him,\" recalled Walsh's son Elmer Jr.<ref name=\"Corman\"/> However, Daley suffered from the general tide against the Democrats while Walsh benefited from being a veteran of World War II.{{sfn|Royko|p=55|ps=none}}\n\n===Courts===\nJarecki, who had been the County Judge since 1922,<ref name=\"Jarecki\">{{cite web |last1=Bolek |first1=Francis |title=Jarecki, Edmund K. |url=http://www.poles.org/db/J_names/Jarecki_EK.html |publisher=Poles in America Foundation |accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref> had such a narrow margin of victory that it was possible that he might have lost as of November 8,<ref name=\"Arlington Heights Herald\"/> and ultimately had a margin of victory of only 8,873 votes in what was the closest election.<ref name=\"Herald\"/>\n\n[[File:Cook County Probate Judge 1946.png|thumb|Results of the probate judge election.]]\nRepublican candidate William Waugh won the Probate Court Judgeship, defeating the Democratic opponent John F. O'Connell.<ref name=\"Arlington Heights Herald\"/>\n\n==Aftermath and legacy==\nThe elections proved to be Kelly's downfall. [[Jacob Arvey]], a Democratic west side boss who had returned from the war, convinced him to resign as chairman.{{sfn|Royko|p=55|ps=none}} In the following year's [[1947 Chicago mayoral election|Chicago mayoral election]] Kelly was replaced by [[Martin Kennelly]] as the Democratic candidate.{{sfn|Royko|p=56|ps=none}}\n\nThe shrieval race would be Daley's only electoral defeat.<ref name=\"Corman\">{{cite news |last1=Corman |first1=Stephen |title=The man who defeated Richard J. Daley |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/45932373/the-man-who-defeated-richard-j-daley/ |accessdate=1 March 2020 |work=Chicago Tribune Magazine |issue=Section 9 |date=February 27, 1977 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Daley became the Chairman of the Cook County Democratic Party Central Committee in 1953 and the Mayor of Chicago in 1955,<ref name=\"Casey\"/> serving both positions until his death in 1976. Walsh served as Sheriff until 1950 but faded from relevance,<ref name=\"Casey\">{{cite news |last1=Casey |first1=Bob |title=Chicago and Mayor Daley the same |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/45930819/elk-grove-herald/ |accessdate=1 March 2020 |work=Elk Grove Herald |volume=18 |issue=267 Section 2 |page=1 |date=March 28, 1975 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> dying in 1962.<ref name=\"Corman\"/>\n\nThe Probate Court, Criminal Court, and County Court were abolished in 1964 upon the formation of the [[Circuit Court of Cook County]] to unify the courts of Cook County into a single jurisdiction. Countywide voting for the Board of Commissioners ended in 1994 when districts were established to elect each commissioner. The Board of Appeals was replaced by a three-member [[Cook County Board of Review|Board of Review]] in 1998.<ref name=\"Board of Review\">{{cite web |title=History of The Board of Review |url=https://cookcountyboardofreview.com/about/history-of-the-board-of-review |publisher=Cook County Board of Review |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Works cited==\n*{{cite book |last=Royko |first=Mike |author-link=Mike Royko |title=Boss: Richard J. Daley of Chicago |year=1971 |url=https://archive.org/details/bossrichardjdale00royk |publisher=Signet |location=New York, New York |ref={{harvid|Royko}}}}\n\n[[Category:Cook County, Illinois elections]]\n[[Category:1946 Illinois elections]]\n\n{{Illinois elections}}\n", "name_user": "Poydoo", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1946_Cook_County,_Illinois_elections"}
{"title_page": "Mariya Poroshina", "text_new": "{{short description|Stage and film actress}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Mariya Poroshina\n| image        = \u041c\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f \u041f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0438\u043d\u0430 (cropped).jpg\n| imagesize    = \n| caption      = Poroshina in 2016\n| birth_name   = Mariya Mikhailovna Poroshina\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1973|11|3|df=yes}} \n| birth_place  = [[Moscow]], [[Russian SFSR]], [[Soviet Union]]\n| nationality  = \n| citizenship  = [[Russia]]n\n| alma_mater   =  \n| other_names  =  \n| occupation   = Actress\n| years_active = 1997\u2013present\n| spouse            = [[Gosha Kutsenko]] (1992 \u2013 1997; divorced)<br>Ilya Drevnov (2009 \u2013 2018; divorced)\n| children          = 5\n| relatives    =\n| awards       = \n}}\n\n'''Mariya Mikhailovna Poroshina''' ({{lang-ru|\u041c\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f \u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0439\u043b\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0430 \u041f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0438\u043d\u0430}}, born 3 November 1973) is a Russian actress.\n\n== Biography ==\nMariya Porochina was born on 1 November 1973, into a family of actors. Her mother, Natalia Petrovna Krasnoyarskaya, now [[director]] at [[Bolshoi Theater]], learned classical singing and performed [[Romance (music)|romance]]) and period songs. Her father, Mikha\u00efl Ivanovitch Porochin, was a soloist in the famous \"Ensemble Berezka\". Her grandmother was an opera singer. Poroshina's parents divorced, and her mother remarries actor Dmitri Yurievich Nazarov. He gets along well with his adopted daughter, checks her homework and questions her. She then has little free time. She studied at school n \u00b0 59 (now 1286), specializing in the study of French, and learned to dance within the troupe of the \"Ensemble Berezka\".\n\nAt the end of her studies, Maria enrolled at the [[Moscow Art Theatre School]], which she left after a year to join the [[Boris Shchukin Theatre Institute]].She directs the program \"Expand the circle\", plays in various productions of the classical and contemporary repertoire, notably at the Pokrovka Theater, under the direction of Sergei Artsibachev. Maria is currently part of Sergei Vinogradov's theater troupe, \"THE THEATER\", where she begins by playing the role of \"'Chlo\u00e9' 'in the play by [[Boris Vian]],''[[Froth on the Daydream]]''.\n\nPorochina took her first steps in the cinema by playing small roles in television series. It is thanks to that of ''Tamara'' in the series entitled The Brigade (2002) and to the main role held in the series Always say: Always (2003) that she knows fame. Then her following main roles on the big screen include, in The 4th Wishes (2003), or, among the fantastic team of [[Timur Bekmambetov]], on the set of [[Night Watch (2004 film)|Night Watch]] (2004). In 2005, Poroshina re-assumes the role of the Great Magic Svetlana in the sequel, [[Day Watch (film)|Day Watch]], a film which at the time achieved the most box office entrances.\n\n== Private life ==\nPoroshina's first husband is the actor [[Gosha Kutsenko]]. Their daughter Polina was born from this union in 1996. In 2007, Polina appeared in the television series \"On the way to the heart\", and in 2010, with her father, the role of  ''Christine'' in '''La compensation'''. Poroshina married actor Ilya Drevnov, with whom she has three daughters: Serafima, born in 2005, Agrafena, born on 18 February 2010 and Glafira, born 3 February 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|accessdate = 2016-02-05|lang = |title = 42-\u043b\u0435\u0442\u043d\u044f\u044f \u041f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0432 \u0447\u0435\u0442\u0432\u0451\u0440\u0442\u044b\u0439 \u0440\u0430\u0437 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0430 \u043c\u0430\u043c\u043e\u0439 |date=4 February 2016 |url = https://deti.mail.ru/news/42-letnyaya-mariya-poroshina-stala-mamoj/ |author=\u0412\u0438\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044f \u0417\u0430\u0439\u0447\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e|publisher =deti.mail.ru}}</ref> They divorced in 2018. She also has a son, Andrei (born 11 January 2019).<ref>{{Cite web |accessdate = 2019-01-31 |lang =  |title = \u042d\u043a\u0441\u043a\u043b\u044e\u0437\u0438\u0432! \u041c\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f \u041f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0430 \u043c\u0430\u043c\u043e\u0439 \u0432 \u043f\u044f\u0442\u044b\u0439 \u0440\u0430\u0437 |date = 11 January 2019 |url = https://7days.ru/stars/privatelife/eksklyuziv-mariya-poroshina-stala-mamoy-v-pyatyy-raz.htm/ |author =  |publisher = 7days.ru |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20190112212336/https://7days.ru/stars/privatelife/eksklyuziv-mariya-poroshina-stala-mamoy-v-pyatyy-raz.htm |archivedate = 2019-01-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|nm1115009|Mariya Poroshina}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Poroshina, Mariya}}\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Russian actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Moscow]]\n[[Category:Russian film actresses]]\n[[Category:Russian stage actresses]]\n[[Category:Russian television actresses]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Stage and film actress}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Mariya Poroshina\n| image        = \u041c\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f \u041f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0438\u043d\u0430 (cropped).jpg\n| imagesize    = \n| caption      = Poroshina in 2016\n| birth_name   = Mariya Mikhailovna Poroshina\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1973|11|3|df=yes}} \n| birth_place  = [[Moscow]], [[Russian SFSR]], [[Soviet Union]]\n| nationality  = \n| citizenship  = [[Russia]]n\n| alma_mater   =  \n| other_names  =  \n| occupation   = Actress\n| years_active = 1997\u2013present\n| spouse            = [[Gosha Kutsenko]] (1992 \u2013 1997; divorced)<br>Ilya Drevnov (2009 \u2013 2018; divorced)\n| children          = 5\n| relatives    =\n| awards       = \n}}\n\n'''Mariya Mikhailovna Poroshina''' ({{lang-ru|\u041c\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f \u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0439\u043b\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0430 \u041f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0438\u043d\u0430}}, born 3 November 1973) is a Russian actress.\n\n== Biography ==\nMariya Porochina was born on 1 November 1973, into a family of actors. Her mother, Natalia Petrovna Krasnoyarskaya, now [[director]] at [[Bolshoi Theater]], learned classical singing and performed [[Romance (music)|romance]]) and period songs. Her father, Mikha\u00efl Ivanovitch Porochin, was a soloist in the famous \"Ensemble Berezka\". Her grandmother was an opera singer. Poroshina's parents divorced, and her mother remarries actor Dmitri Yurievich Nazarov. He gets along well with his adopted daughter, checks her homework and questions her. She then has little free time. She studied at school n \u00b0 59 (now 1286), specializing in the study of French, and learned to dance within the troupe of the \"Ensemble Berezka\".\n\nAt the end of her studies, Maria enrolled at the [[Moscow Art Theatre School]], which she left after a year to join the [[Boris Shchukin Theatre Institute]].She directs the program \"Expand the circle\", plays in various productions of the classical and contemporary repertoire, notably at the Pokrovka Theater, under the direction of Sergei Artsibachev. Maria is currently part of Sergei Vinogradov's theater troupe, \"THE THEATER\", where she begins by playing the role of \"'Chlo\u00e9' 'in the play by [[Boris Vian]],''[[Froth on the Daydream]]''.\n\nPorochina took her first steps in the cinema by playing small roles in television series. It is thanks to that of ''Tamara'' in the series entitled The Brigade (2002) and to the main role held in the series Always say: Always (2003) that she knows fame. Then her following main roles on the big screen include, in The 4th Wishes (2003), or, among the fantastic team of [[Timur Bekmambetov]], on the set of [[Night Watch (2004 film)|Night Watch]] (2004). In 2005, Poroshina re-assumes the role of the Great Magic Svetlana in the sequel, [[Day Watch (film)|Day Watch]], a film which at the time achieved the most box office entrances.\n\n== Private life ==\nPoroshina's first husband is the actor [[Gosha Kutsenko]]. Their daughter Polina was born from this union in 1996. In 2007, Polina appeared in the television series \"On the way to the heart\", and in 2010, with her father, the role of  ''Christine'' in '''La compensation'''. Poroshina married actor Ilya Drevnov, with whom she has three daughters: Serafima, born in 2005, Agrafena, born on 18 February 2010 and Glafira, born 3 February 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|accessdate = 2016-02-05|lang = |title = 42-\u043b\u0435\u0442\u043d\u044f\u044f \u041f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0432 \u0447\u0435\u0442\u0432\u0451\u0440\u0442\u044b\u0439 \u0440\u0430\u0437 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0430 \u043c\u0430\u043c\u043e\u0439 |date=4 \u0444\u0435\u0432\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044f 2016 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430|url = https://deti.mail.ru/news/42-letnyaya-mariya-poroshina-stala-mamoj/ |author=\u0412\u0438\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044f \u0417\u0430\u0439\u0447\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e|publisher =// deti.mail.ru}}</ref> They divorced in 2018. She also has a son, Andrei (born 11 January 2019).<ref>{{Cite web |accessdate = 2019-01-31 |lang =  |title = \u042d\u043a\u0441\u043a\u043b\u044e\u0437\u0438\u0432! \u041c\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f \u041f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0430 \u043c\u0430\u043c\u043e\u0439 \u0432 \u043f\u044f\u0442\u044b\u0439 \u0440\u0430\u0437 |date = 11 \u044f\u043d\u0432\u0430\u0440\u044f 2019 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 |url = https://7days.ru/stars/privatelife/eksklyuziv-mariya-poroshina-stala-mamoy-v-pyatyy-raz.htm/ |author =  |publisher = // 7days.ru |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20190112212336/https://7days.ru/stars/privatelife/eksklyuziv-mariya-poroshina-stala-mamoy-v-pyatyy-raz.htm |archivedate = 2019-01-12 |deadlink = yes }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|nm1115009|Mariya Poroshina}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Poroshina, Mariya}}\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Russian actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Moscow]]\n[[Category:Russian film actresses]]\n[[Category:Russian stage actresses]]\n[[Category:Russian television actresses]]\n", "name_user": "John B123", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed cite errors", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mariya_Poroshina"}
{"title_page": "Mark Immelman", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Mark Immelman\n| image = [[File:Mark immelman2.jpg|thumb|Immelman working on course for PGA TOUR Live]]\n| caption = \n| birth_name = Mark Immelman\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1970|10|2}}\n| birth_place = [[Somerset West]], [[South Africa]]\n| education = [[Columbus State University]]\n| occupation = Sports Announcer, Golf Coach, Author\n| employer = \n| years_active = \n| spouse = Tracy Martin-Immelman\n| children = 2\n}}\n\n'''Mark Immelman''' (born October 2, 1970) is a [[Demographics of South Africa|South African]] [[sportscaster]], [[golf]] [[Coach (sport)|coach]] and [[author]]. \n\nImmelman is currently the host of the On the Mark podcast on pgatour.com.<ref>https://www.pgatour.com/radio/on-the-mark.html</ref> He also covers live golf for the [[PGA Tour|PGA TOUR]] on their live-streaming mobile app, PGA TOUR Live, on [[Sirius XM PGA Tour Radio|SiriusXM PGA TOUR Radio]]<ref>http://investor.siriusxm.com/investor-overview/press-releases/press-release-details/2018/PGA-TOUR-SiriusXM-Agree-to-Four-Year-Extension/default.aspx</ref> and for [[Golf Channel]] and [[CBS Sports]].<ref>https://www.viacomcbspressexpress.com/cbs-sports/shows/golf-on-cbs/bios?id=mark-immelman</ref> In addition to his broadcasting career, he's also the Director of Golf at [[Columbus State University]] <ref>http://www.csucougars.com/mobile/staff.aspx?staff=35</ref> and the author of ''Scandalously Simple: The Easy Way to Accurate Golf Shots''.<ref>https://itunes.apple.com/us/book/scandalously-simple/id960855999?mt=11</ref>\n\nMark is the older brother of [[2008 Masters Tournament|2008 Masters]] champion, [[Trevor Immelman]]<ref>https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20150409006279/en/Mark-Immelman-Brother-2008-Masters-Champion-Trevor</ref> and son of former South African [[Sunshine Tour]] commissioner, Johan Immelman.\n\n==Amateur Career==\nIn four seasons playing for Columbus State, Immelman was a three-time All-American (1992, 94, 95) and a two-time Academic All-American<ref>http://collegiategolf.com/component/option,com_honor/Itemid,39/view,default/</ref> while winning multiple national championships (1992, 94) with Columbus State.<ref>https://www.ncaa.com/history/golf-men/d2</ref>\n\n==Broadcasting Career==\nMark got his start in golf broadcast when he made a number of appearances as a guest announcer on [[SuperSport|SuperSport TV]] in South Africa for various co-sanctioned Sunshine Tour events including the [[South African Open (golf)|South African Open]] and the [[Alfred Dunhill Championship]]. In those early days, he was also afforded the opportunity to be a part of the European Tour Productions [[broadcasting|broadcast]] crew for [[Joburg Open|the Joburg Open]] on [[PGA European Tour|the European Tour]].\n \nHis career in broadcast on The PGA TOUR began when he was included on the SiriusXM PGA TOUR Radio crew for the 2012 [[Greenbrier Classic|A Military Tribute at the Greenbrier]]. Mark parlayed that outing into a 6-year tenure as one of Sirius XM PGA TOUR Radio\u2019s leading play-by-play voices. His radio experience led to him hosting his own live streaming radio show called \u201cOn the Mark\u201d on pgatour.com. The show aired for three days per week in 2015 and after one season the PGA TOUR driven radio initiative morphed into a podcast called \u201cOn the Mark.\u201d<ref>https://www.pgatour.com/news/2016/08/22/PGA-TOUR-podcasts.html</ref> The first podcast was released in February 2016, and to date it has been downloaded over 2.5 Million times in over 125 countries.\n \nMark\u2019s broadcast work for the PGA TOUR also included him being a part of the \u201cLive @\u201d crew for pgatour.com for a short stint. The PGA TOUR Entertainment Network grew steadily and became a digital subscription-based streaming service called PGA TOUR LIVE<ref>https://www.pgatour.com/company/2015/04/28/pga-tour-live-digital-subscription-service.html</ref>.  Mark (among others) was hired as one of the in-studio analysts as well as an on-course announcer for PGA TOUR LIVE and has been a prominent announcer with the network since its inception.\n \nWhile working for PGA TOUR LIVE, Mark has also appeared on [[DirecTV|DirecTV\u2019s]] featured groups coverage of various PGA TOUR events, and the DirecTV LaunchPad Channel as an announcer and analyst.<ref>https://www.directv.com/tv/Launch-Pad-Channel-Mk9DOVQ5Tjh3TU09/SHOTLink-Channel-Y2ZyYjFMbWdXWjBHNklYazVGT1Yxdz09</ref>\n \nHis work on PGA TOUR LIVE led to him being hired by CBS Sports as a part of their [[Ultra-high-definition television|4K]] Television broadcast of the [[2016 PGA Championship]] at [[Baltusrol Golf Club|Baltusrol]], [[New Jersey|NJ]].  His work in 4K expanded when he was offered analyst roles on The Masters broadcasts of \u201cMasters On the Range,\u201d \u201cFeatured Groups\u201d and \u201cAmen Corner.\u201d<ref>https://www.viacomcbspressexpress.com/cbs-sports/releases/view?id=49842</ref> His career in the 4K broadcasts also had him being used as an on-course announcer, and he continued to grow and impress in his role at CBS Sports and he was eventually promoted and became a member of the CBS Sports Network show announce crew in 2018.<ref>https://www.viacomcbspressexpress.com/cbs-sports/shows/golf-on-cbs/bios?id=mark-immelman</ref>\n \nMark is also an analyst on the CBS Sports digital podcast \u201cThe First Cut\u201d and a golf analyst for CBS Sports HQ.<ref>https://www.cbssports.com/podcasts/the-first-cut-golf-podcast/</ref>\n \nIn his combined radio and television career, Mark has broadcasted two of the four [[Men's major golf championships|Majors]] in professional golf ([[Masters Tournament|The Masters]] and [[PGA Championship|the PGA Championship]]).  He has also been an announcer at a number of [[World Golf Championships]] (WGC) events.  He has also announced and called three [[Presidents Cup|Presidents Cups]].\n\n==Awards==\n2009 [[NCAA Division II]] Coach of the Year <ref>http://www.csucougars.com/mobile/staff.aspx?staff=35</ref><br>\n2017 Columbus State Athletics [[List of halls and walks of fame|Hall of Fame]] inductee <ref>http://csucougars.com/news/2017/3/16/general-2017-csu-hall-of-fame-class-announced.aspx</ref>\n\n==Personal Life==\nImmelman lives with his wife, Tracy, and two daughters in [[Columbus, Georgia|Columbus]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]].\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*[http://markimmelman.com/ Mark Immelman official website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Immelman, Mark}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:College golf coaches in the United States]]\n[[Category:College golfers in the United States]]\n[[Category:Columbus State Cougars athletes]]\n[[Category:Golf writers and broadcasters]]\n[[Category:People from Somerset West]]\n[[Category:South African emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Cape Town]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Mark Immelman\n| image = [[File:Mark immelman2.jpg|thumb|Mark Immelman working on course for PGA TOUR Live]]\n| caption = \n| birth_name = Mark Immelman\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1970|10|2}}\n| birth_place = [[Somerset West]], [[South Africa]]\n| education = [[Columbus State University]]\n| occupation = Sports Announcer, Golf Coach, Author\n| employer = \n| years_active = \n| spouse = Tracy Martin-Immelman\n| children = 2\n}}\n\n'''Mark Immelman''' (born October 2, 1970) is a [[Demographics of South Africa|South African]] [[sportscaster]], [[golf]] [[Coach (sport)|coach]] and [[author]]. \n\nImmelman is currently the host of the On the Mark podcast on pgatour.com.<ref>https://www.pgatour.com/radio/on-the-mark.html</ref> He also covers live golf for the [[PGA Tour|PGA TOUR]] on their live-streaming mobile app, PGA TOUR Live, on [[Sirius XM PGA Tour Radio|SiriusXM PGA TOUR Radio]]<ref>http://investor.siriusxm.com/investor-overview/press-releases/press-release-details/2018/PGA-TOUR-SiriusXM-Agree-to-Four-Year-Extension/default.aspx</ref> and for [[Golf Channel]] and [[CBS Sports]].<ref>https://www.viacomcbspressexpress.com/cbs-sports/shows/golf-on-cbs/bios?id=mark-immelman</ref> In addition to his broadcasting career, he's also the Director of Golf at [[Columbus State University]] <ref>http://www.csucougars.com/mobile/staff.aspx?staff=35</ref> and the author of ''Scandalously Simple: The Easy Way to Accurate Golf Shots''.<ref>https://itunes.apple.com/us/book/scandalously-simple/id960855999?mt=11</ref>\n\nMark is the older brother of [[2008 Masters Tournament|2008 Masters]] champion, [[Trevor Immelman]]<ref>https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20150409006279/en/Mark-Immelman-Brother-2008-Masters-Champion-Trevor</ref> and son of former South African [[Sunshine Tour]] commissioner, Johan Immelman.\n\n==Amateur Career==\nIn four seasons playing for Columbus State, Immelman was a three-time All-American (1992, 94, 95) and a two-time Academic All-American<ref>http://collegiategolf.com/component/option,com_honor/Itemid,39/view,default/</ref> while winning multiple national championships (1992, 94) with Columbus State.<ref>https://www.ncaa.com/history/golf-men/d2</ref>\n\n==Broadcasting Career==\nMark got his start in golf broadcast when he made a number of appearances as a guest announcer on [[SuperSport|SuperSport TV]] in South Africa for various co-sanctioned Sunshine Tour events including the [[South African Open (golf)|South African Open]] and the [[Alfred Dunhill Championship]]. In those early days, he was also afforded the opportunity to be a part of the European Tour Productions [[broadcasting|broadcast]] crew for [[Joburg Open|the Joburg Open]] on [[PGA European Tour|the European Tour]].\n \nHis career in broadcast on The PGA TOUR began when he was included on the SiriusXM PGA TOUR Radio crew for the 2012 [[Greenbrier Classic|A Military Tribute at the Greenbrier]]. Mark parlayed that outing into a 6-year tenure as one of Sirius