{"title_page": "Myla Goldberg", "text_new": "[[Image:Myla Goldberg by David Shankbone.jpg|thumb|Myla Goldberg at the 2007 [[Brooklyn Book Festival]]]]\n'''Myla Goldberg''' (born November 19, 1971) is an American novelist and musician.\n\n==Biography==\nGoldberg was born into a [[Jew]]ish family.  She was raised in [[Laurel, Maryland]], and graduated from [[Eleanor Roosevelt High School (Maryland)|Eleanor Roosevelt High School]], where she was one of the [[Scholastic Art & Writing Awards]] winners in 1989.<ref>{{cite news |title=Put Paper to Pen and Spell out Eliza. A Very Happy Birthday to Myla Goldberg! |url=http://blog.artandwriting.org/2011/11/19/happy-birthday-to-writer-musician-and-scholastic-awards-alum-myla-goldberg/ |work=Scholastic Art & Writing Awards |date=November 19, 2011}}</ref>  She majored in [[English major|English]] at [[Oberlin College]], graduating in 1996.<ref name=Geek>{{cite journal |url=http://www.grendel.org/milgeek/myla.html |title=Interview: Myla Goldberg |work=Militant Geek |issue=3 |date=Fall 2000}}</ref> She spent a year teaching and writing in [[Prague]] (providing the germ of her book of essays ''Time's Magpie'', which explores her favorite places within the city), then moved to [[Brooklyn, New York]], where she still lives with her husband ([[Jason Little (cartoonist)|Jason Little]]) and two daughter.\n\nGoldberg is an accomplished amateur musician.  She plays the [[banjo]] and [[accordion]] in a Brooklyn-based indie rock quartet, ''[[The Walking Hellos]]''.  She has performed with The Galerkin Method and the [[Bindlestiff Family Cirkus]].  She formerly collaborated with the New York art collective [[Flux Factory]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fluxfactory.org/fluxers/myla-goldberg/ |title=Myla Goldberg |publisher=Flux Factory |date=January 16, 2007}}</ref>  She has contributed song lyrics to the musical group [[One Ring Zero]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oneringzero.com/?page_id=15 |title=The Official One Ring Zero Thanks Page |publisher=One Ring Zero |accessdate=May 28, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Bookbits - 2010-11-05 Myla Goldberg-The False Friend.vorb.oga|thumb|right|Myla Goldberg talks about The False Friend on Bookbits radio.]]\nWhile in Prague, Goldberg completed her first novel, ''Kirkus'', a story of an Eastern European circus troupe engulfed by the onset of [[World War II]].  She gave it to an agent who shopped it for 18 months, but it was not published by the time she had begun working on ''Bee Season'', so it was shelved.\n\nAfter returning to Brooklyn Goldberg took several jobs, including working on a production of a [[Stephen King]] horror movie.  She was let go from that job, which brought an unforeseen benefit - the six months of unemployment benefits checks gave her sufficient time to finish ''Bee Season'' (\"It was a grant, as far as I was concerned\", she told an Oberlin student interviewer in 2005).<ref name=Geek/>\n\nGoldberg's first published novel was ''[[Bee Season]]'' ([[2000 in literature|2000]]), portraying the breakdown of a family and the spiritual explorations of its two children amid a series of [[spelling bee]]s.  It was a popular and critical success, and was [[Bee Season (film)|adapted into a film]] in 2005. She has also published short stories in ''Virgin Fiction'', ''Eclectic Literary Forum'', ''[[New American Writing]]'', ''[[Timothy McSweeney's Quarterly Concern|McSweeney's]]'' and ''[[Harper's Magazine|Harpers Magazine]]''.  She reviews books for ''[[The New York Times]]'' and ''[[Bookforum]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bookbrowse.com/biographies/index.cfm?author_number=1205 |title=Myla Goldberg Biography |publisher=BookBrowse |accessdate=May 28, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005 Goldberg published a second novel, ''[[Wickett's Remedy]]'' ([[2005 in literature|2005]]), which is set during the [[1918 flu pandemic|1918 influenza epidemic]].  In 2009 she said she was working on a third novel, to be titled ''The False Friend'', due in 2010.  It describes a woman whose memory is jogged, causing her to revisit a tragic event in her youth.  \"It's about memory, hometowns and the adults children turn into,\" Goldberg told an interviewer.<ref>{{cite news |last=Long |first=Karen R. |url=http://www.cleveland.com/books/index.ssf/2009/03/jonathem_lethem_myla_goldberg.html |title=Jonathan Lethem, Myla Goldberg and Colson Whitehead speak of cartoons, criticism and their upcoming work |work=The Plain Dealer |date=March 4, 2009}}</ref>\n\n\"[[Song for Myla Goldberg]]\" is track six on [[The Decemberists]]' album ''[[Her Majesty The Decemberists]].'' It makes a handful of allusions to ''Bee Season''.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.randomhouse.com/boldtype/0500/goldberg/ Myla Goldberg] at Random House.\n*{{IMDb name | id=1503335 | name=Myla Goldberg}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Goldberg, Myla}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:American satirists]]\n[[Category:American women short story writers]]\n[[Category:American women novelists]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:Oberlin College alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Laurel, Maryland]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Women satirists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American short story writers]]\n[[Category:American women non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n", "text_old": "[[Image:Myla Goldberg by David Shankbone.jpg|thumb|Myla Goldberg at the 2007 [[Brooklyn Book Festival]]]]\n'''Myla Goldberg''' (born November 19, 1971) is an American novelist and musician.\n\n==Biography==\nGoldberg was born into a [[Jew]]ish family.  She was raised in [[Laurel, Maryland]], and graduated from [[Eleanor Roosevelt High School (Maryland)|Eleanor Roosevelt High School]], where was won of the [[Scholastic Art & Writing Awards]] winners in 1989.<ref>{{cite news |title=Put Paper to Pen and Spell out Eliza. A Very Happy Birthday to Myla Goldberg! |url=http://blog.artandwriting.org/2011/11/19/happy-birthday-to-writer-musician-and-scholastic-awards-alum-myla-goldberg/ |work=Scholastic Art & Writing Awards |date=November 19, 2011}}</ref>  She majored in [[English major|English]] at [[Oberlin College]], graduating in 1996.<ref name=Geek>{{cite journal |url=http://www.grendel.org/milgeek/myla.html |title=Interview: Myla Goldberg |work=Militant Geek |issue=3 |date=Fall 2000}}</ref> She spent a year teaching and writing in [[Prague]] (providing the germ of her book of essays ''Time's Magpie'', which explores her favorite places within the city), then moved to [[Brooklyn, New York]], where she still lives with her husband ([[Jason Little (cartoonist)|Jason Little]]) and two daughter.\n\nGoldberg is an accomplished amateur musician.  She plays the [[banjo]] and [[accordion]] in a Brooklyn-based indie rock quartet, ''[[The Walking Hellos]]''.  She has performed with The Galerkin Method and the [[Bindlestiff Family Cirkus]].  She formerly collaborated with the New York art collective [[Flux Factory]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fluxfactory.org/fluxers/myla-goldberg/ |title=Myla Goldberg |publisher=Flux Factory |date=January 16, 2007}}</ref>  She has contributed song lyrics to the musical group [[One Ring Zero]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oneringzero.com/?page_id=15 |title=The Official One Ring Zero Thanks Page |publisher=One Ring Zero |accessdate=May 28, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Bookbits - 2010-11-05 Myla Goldberg-The False Friend.vorb.oga|thumb|right|Myla Goldberg talks about The False Friend on Bookbits radio.]]\nWhile in Prague, Goldberg completed her first novel, ''Kirkus'', a story of an Eastern European circus troupe engulfed by the onset of [[World War II]].  She gave it to an agent who shopped it for 18 months, but it was not published by the time she had begun working on ''Bee Season'', so it was shelved.\n\nAfter returning to Brooklyn Goldberg took several jobs, including working on a production of a [[Stephen King]] horror movie.  She was let go from that job, which brought an unforeseen benefit - the six months of unemployment benefits checks gave her sufficient time to finish ''Bee Season'' (\"It was a grant, as far as I was concerned\", she told an Oberlin student interviewer in 2005).<ref name=Geek/>\n\nGoldberg's first published novel was ''[[Bee Season]]'' ([[2000 in literature|2000]]), portraying the breakdown of a family and the spiritual explorations of its two children amid a series of [[spelling bee]]s.  It was a popular and critical success, and was [[Bee Season (film)|adapted into a film]] in 2005. She has also published short stories in ''Virgin Fiction'', ''Eclectic Literary Forum'', ''[[New American Writing]]'', ''[[Timothy McSweeney's Quarterly Concern|McSweeney's]]'' and ''[[Harper's Magazine|Harpers Magazine]]''.  She reviews books for ''[[The New York Times]]'' and ''[[Bookforum]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bookbrowse.com/biographies/index.cfm?author_number=1205 |title=Myla Goldberg Biography |publisher=BookBrowse |accessdate=May 28, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005 Goldberg published a second novel, ''[[Wickett's Remedy]]'' ([[2005 in literature|2005]]), which is set during the [[1918 flu pandemic|1918 influenza epidemic]].  In 2009 she said she was working on a third novel, to be titled ''The False Friend'', due in 2010.  It describes a woman whose memory is jogged, causing her to revisit a tragic event in her youth.  \"It's about memory, hometowns and the adults children turn into,\" Goldberg told an interviewer.<ref>{{cite news |last=Long |first=Karen R. |url=http://www.cleveland.com/books/index.ssf/2009/03/jonathem_lethem_myla_goldberg.html |title=Jonathan Lethem, Myla Goldberg and Colson Whitehead speak of cartoons, criticism and their upcoming work |work=The Plain Dealer |date=March 4, 2009}}</ref>\n\n\"[[Song for Myla Goldberg]]\" is track six on [[The Decemberists]]' album ''[[Her Majesty The Decemberists]].'' It makes a handful of allusions to ''Bee Season''.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.randomhouse.com/boldtype/0500/goldberg/ Myla Goldberg] at Random House.\n*{{IMDb name | id=1503335 | name=Myla Goldberg}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Goldberg, Myla}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:American satirists]]\n[[Category:American women short story writers]]\n[[Category:American women novelists]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:Oberlin College alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Laurel, Maryland]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Women satirists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American short story writers]]\n[[Category:American women non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n", "name_user": "WereSpielChequers", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBiography:Typo fixing, replaced: won of \u2192  one of", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Myla_Goldberg"}
{"title_page": "Nigerian Army", "text_new": "{{Short description|Land warfare branch of Nigeria's military}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox military unit\n| unit_name = Nigerian Army\n| image = Emblem of the Nigerian Army.svg\n| caption = Emblem of the Nigerian Army\n| dates = \n| country = {{flag|Nigeria}}\n| type = [[Army]]\n| size = 200,000 (2016)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.livegist.com.ng/nigerian-army-76rri-list-successful-shortlisted-candidates-zonal-screening|title=Nigerian Army 76RRI List of Successful Shortlisted Candidates for Zonal Screening|website=Livegist.com.ng|accessdate=20 July 2018}}</ref>\n| command_structure = \n| garrison = [[Abuja]]\n| garrison_label = [[Headquarters]]\n| motto = ''\"Victory is from God alone\"''\n| colors = \n| colors_label = \n| battles = [[Congo Crisis]]<br/>[[Nigerian Civil War]]<br >[[First Liberian Civil War]]<br >[[Sierra Leone Civil War]]<br >[[Conflict in the Niger Delta]]<br >[[Boko Haram insurgency]]<br >[[Northern Mali War]]<br >[[Invasion of the Gambia]]\n| website = http://army.mil.ng/<!-- Commanders -->\n| commander1 = [[Muhammadu Buhari|President Muhammadu Buhari]]\n| commander1_label = [[President of Nigeria|Commander-in-Chief]]\n| commander2 = [[Tukur Yusuf Buratai|Lt General Tukur Yusuf Buratai]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nigerian-army.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=63&Itemid=1&fontstyle=f-default |title=Archived copy |access-date=3 August 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725192650/http://www.nigerian-army.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=63&Itemid=1&fontstyle=f-default |archive-date=25 July 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n| commander2_label = [[Chief of Army Staff (Nigeria)|Chief of Army Staff]]\n| notable_commanders = General Aguiyi Ironsi\n\nGeneral Yakubu Gowon (Retired)\n\nLieutenant General [[Theophilus Danjuma]] (Retired)\n\nGeneral [[Ibrahim Babangida]]a (Retired)\nGeneral [[Sani Abacha]] (Deceased)\n\nMajor General Alwali Kazir (Retired)\n\nLieutenant General [[Abdulrahman Dambazau]] (Retired)\n\nLieutenant General [[Azubuike Ihejirika]] (Retired)\n\nLieutenant General Kenneth T. J. Minimah (Retired)\n| identification_symbol = [[File:Flag of the Nigerian Army Headquarters.svg|200px|border|center]]\n| identification_symbol_label = Flag\n| identification_symbol_2 = \n| identification_symbol_2_label = <!-- Aircraft -->\n| aircraft_electronic = \n| aircraft_helicopter = \n| aircraft_transport = \n| start_date = 1960\u2013present\n| ceremonial_chief = \n| ceremonial_chief_label = \n}}\n\nThe '''Nigerian army''' ('''NA''') is the largest component of the [[Nigerian Armed Forces]], and is responsible for [[land warfare]] operations. It is governed by the Nigerian Army Council (NAC).<ref name=\"Red Cross\">{{cite web|url=https://www.icrc.org/applic/ihl/ihl-nat.nsf/0/049ea0330082bc31c12576ea005be4a3/$FILE/ARMED%20FORCES%20ACT.pdf|title=Nigerian Armed Forces Act, 1994|author=Parliament of Nigeria|publisher=International Red Cross|accessdate=12 March 2015}}</ref> It bears the brunt of the nation's security challenges, notably the [[Boko Haram insurgency]].<ref name=\"ZA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.defenceweb.co.za/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=32118:nigerian-armed-forces&catid=119:african-militaries|title=Nigerian Armed Forces|author=Guy Martin|website=Defenceweb.co.za|accessdate=15 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\nThe original elements of the [[Royal West African Frontier Force]] (RWAFF) in Nigeria were formed in 1900. During the [[Second World War]], British-trained Nigerian troops saw action with the [[1st (West Africa) Infantry Brigade]], the [[81st (West Africa) Division|81st]] and the [[82nd (West Africa) Division]]s which fought in the [[East African Campaign (World War II)]] and in the Far East.\n\nThe roots of the ethnic cleavages which started to rip through the army after independence had some of their origins in British recruiting practices, with line infantry and the artillery being raised from the North, but during the expansion of the force during the [[Second World War]] a large proportion of more educated southerners being brought in to take up posts that required more technical training. Like in [[Ghana Army|Ghana]], there was significant pressure to \"Nigerianize\" the armed forces, with, for example, two officers being promoted to Brigadier as a concession to public opinion on the occasion of the last British commander arriving in Lagos. From a force of 8,000 in five infantry battalions and supporting units,<ref>Gutteridge, Military in African Politics, 1969, 97.</ref> strength rose to around 120,000 in three divisions by the end of the [[Nigerian Civil War]] in 1970.<ref>Scott report, ''Sunday Telegraph'', 11 January 1970, via N.J. Miners, ''The Nigerian Army 1956-65'', Methuen and Co. Ltd, London, 1971, p. 229</ref> In terms of doctrine, the task of the Federal Nigerian army did not fundamentally change: its task remained to close with and defeat an organized enemy.\n\nThe rapid expansion saw a severe decline in troop quality.<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/africa/the-nigerian-military-is-so-broken-its-soldiers-are-refusing-to-fight/2015/05/06/d56fabac-dcae-11e4-b6d7-b9bc8acf16f7_story.html</ref> The Nigerian expansion process led to an extreme shortage of commissioned officers, with newly created lieutenant-colonels commanding brigades, and platoons and companies often commanded by sergeants and warrant officers. This resulted in tentative [[command and control|command-and-control]] and in rudimentary staff work.<ref>Neville Brown, \"The Nigerian Civil War,\" Military Review, vol. 48, October 1968, p. 28, cited in Major Michael Stafford, Quick Kill in Slow Motion, Marine Corps CSC, 1984, at http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/library/report/1984/SMR.htm</ref> One result of the weak direction was that the Federals' three divisions fought independently, and competed for men and material. Writing in a 1984 study, Major Michael Stafford of the US Marine Corps noted that \"Inexperienced, poorly trained and ineptly led soldiers manifested their lack of professionalism and indiscipline by massacres of innocent civilians and a failure to effectively execute infantry tactics.\"<ref>Stafford study, 1984</ref> Among the results was the 1967 [[Asaba massacre]].\n\nThe influence of individual personalities is generally greater in the armies of developing states, as they tend to have weaker institutional frameworks. Key personalities involved in Nigeria included then-Colonel [[Olusegun Obasanjo]]. Obasanjo is particularly important due to his efforts to reorganize his command, [[3rd Division (Nigeria)|3 Division]], during the civil war to improve its logistics and administration. The reorganization he instituted made the Division capable of carrying out the offensive that ended the civil war.\n\nThe U.S. intelligence community concluded in November 1970 that \"..The [[Nigerian Civil War]] ended with relatively little rancor. The Igbos are accepted as fellow citizens in many parts of Nigeria, but not in some areas of former [[Biafra]] where they were once dominant. Igboland is an overpopulated, economically depressed area where massive unemployment is likely to continue for many years.<ref name=NIE64-2-70>{{citation|title=National Intelligence Estimate 64.2-70: Prospects for Postwar Nigeria |author=Central Intelligence Agency |url=http://www.state.gov/documents/organization/53862.pdf |date=2 November 1970 |publisher=[[United States Department of State]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/20090809041637/http://www.state.gov/documents/organization/53862.pdf |archivedate=9 August 2009 }}</ref>\n{{check quotation}}\nThe U.S. analysts said that \"..Nigeria is still very much a tribal society...\" where local and tribal alliances count more than \"national attachment. General [[Yakubu Gowon]], head of the Federal Military Government (FMG) is the accepted national leader and his popularity has grown since the end of the war. The FMG is neither very efficient nor dynamic, but the recent announcement that it intends to retain power for six more years has generated little opposition so far. The Nigerian Army, vastly expanded during the war, is both the main support to the FMG and the chief threat to it. The troops are poorly trained and disciplined and some of the officers are turning to conspiracies and plotting. We think Gowon will have great difficulty in staying in office through the period which he said is necessary before the turnover of power to civilians. His sudden removal would dim the prospects for Nigerian stability.\"\n\nThe Nigerian Army fought the Civil War significantly under-resourced; Obasanjo's memoirs chronicle the lack of any stocks of extra equipment for mobilisation and the \"haphazard and unreliable system of procurement and provisioning\" which lasted for the entire period of the war.<ref>Olusegun Obasanjo, ''My Command: An Account of the Nigerian Civil War'', Heinemann, Ibadan/London/Nairobi, 1980, p. 61</ref> Arms embargoes imposed by several Western countries made the situation more difficult.\n\nAt the end of the Civil War, the three divisions of the Army were reorganised into four divisions, with each controlling territories running from North to South in order to deemphasise the former regional structure. Each division thus had access to the sea thereby making triservice cooperation and logistic support easier. This deployment formula was later abandoned in favour of the present assignment of sectors to the divisions. Thus 1 Division with HQ at Kaduna is allocated the North West sector; 2 Division with HQ at Ibadan South West sector, 3 Division with HQ at Jos North East sector and 82 Division with HQ at Enugu South East sector.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://logbaby.com/directory/nigerian-army_6193.html|title=Nigerian Army Logbaby|website=logbaby.com|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref>\n\nIts formations include the [[1st Division (Nigeria)|1 Division]], headquartered in [[Kaduna]] in the north-west, and [[2 Division (Nigeria)|2 Division]] (HQ [[Ibadan]] in the South-West, which includes 32 Artillery Brigade at [[Abeokuta]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisdayonline.com/archive/2004/04/20/20040420spo06.html|title=Home|website=Thisdayonline.com|accessdate=15 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110115213808/http://www.thisdayonline.com/archive/2004/04/20/20040420spo06.html|archive-date=15 January 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> 2nd Division also possibly includes 4 Brigade at [[Benin City]], with 19 Battalion at [[Okitipupa]] and 195 Battalion at [[Agenebode]]. 52 Signal Regiment may be the divisional signals unit. [[3rd Division (Nigeria)|3 Division]]'s headquarters is at Rukuba Cantonment, [[Jos]], in the North-East, and includes 21 Armoured Brigade [[Maiduguri]], 23 Brigade [[Yola, Nigeria|Yola]], and 33 Artillery Brigades.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nigerian-army.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=16&Itemid=27 |title=Archived copy |access-date=3 August 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110213043432/http://www.nigerian-army.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=16&Itemid=27 |archive-date=13 February 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[81st Division (Nigeria)|81st Division]] (Amphibious) HQ in Lagos, which includes the 9 Brigade, based at the [[Ikeja]] compound in Lagos, [[82nd Division (Nigeria)|82nd Division]] (Airborne and Amphibious) HQ in [[Enugu]] in the South-East, which includes the 2 Brigade at Port Harcourt, 13 Brigade at Calabar and the 34th Artillery Brigade at [[Obinze]]/[[Owerri]]. The Composite Division at Enugu was formed in 1964 as 4 Division, in 1975 became Lagos Garrison Organization; in 1981 became 4 Composite Division; became a Composite Division in May 2002.<ref>Orbat.com, [https://web.archive.org/web/20060316181350/http://www.ordersofbattle.darkscape.net/site/cwa_2006/display%20version.htm#_ftnref54 Concise World Armies 2006]</ref> 3rd Armoured Division was responsible in 1983 for the security of areas bordering [[Chad]].<ref>Jimi Peters, The Nigerian military and the state, I.B. Tauris, 1997, p. 174, via [[Google Books]]</ref>\n\t \nLagos and Abuja have garrison commands, with the Lagos garrison as large as a division. 81st Division was previously the youngest division, formed on 26 May 2002 when the Lagos Garrison Command (as it then was) was upgraded to divisional status. The Division, therefore, inherited the security roles hitherto performed by the defunct Lagos Garrison Command.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nigerian-army.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18&Itemid=71 |title=Archived copy |access-date=3 August 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725192640/http://www.nigerian-army.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18&Itemid=71 |archive-date=25 July 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> However a later undated article in a Nigerian online newspaper says the 81st Division was later again renamed the Lagos Garrison Command. In the 1980s, the Army's brigades included the 7th Infantry Brigade in Sokoto. There are also Divisional Artillery Brigades, among which are the 32 and 34 Artillery Brigades,<ref>Saxone Akhaine, [http://www.guardiannewsngr.com/news/article12//indexn3_html?pdate=131008&ptitle=Army%20chief%20decries%20military's%20%20involvement%20in%20politics&cpdate=131008 Army chief decries military's involvement in politics], Guardian, Kaduna, 13 October 2008</ref> ordnance corps units as well as Combat Engineer Regiments, and many other service support units spread across the country.\n\t \nThe 7th Division (also known as JTF-RO) was established in August 2013 for the war against [[Boko Haram]]. The creation of the new division brought to six the number of divisions. The 7th division is headquartered in Maiduguri.<ref name=\"globalsecurity.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/nigeria/7div.htm|title=Nigeria - 7th Infantry Division|author=John Pike|website=Globalsecurity.org|accessdate=15 February 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"globalsecurity.org\"/> The division includes a combat motorcycle unit as part of its 25th Task Force Brigade.<ref name=dw20190229>{{cite web|url=http://www.defenseworld.net/news/15460/Nigerian_Army_Inducts_Combat_Motorbikes_Battalion_To_Fight_Boko_Haram#.WGwzPlKsBZE|title=Nigerian Army Inducts Combat Motorbikes Battalion To Fight Boko Haram|publisher=Defense World|date=29 February 2016|accessdate=3 January 2017}}</ref> The purpose of this unit is stated as securing roads in Yobe and serving as a force multiplier in combat operations.<ref name=dw20190229/>. Training and Doctrine Command formed in 1981, and is located at [[Minna]]. It supervises the Army's schools, including the Depot. The Army sponsors the [[Nigerian Military School]] at [[Zaria]].\n\n==Structure==\n{{cleanup|reason=Article needs better organization, structure, and references|date=July 2015}}\n\n{{Location map many | Nigeria\n| width = 310\n| float = right\n| caption = <center>Divisions of Nigeria</center>\n| label = <small>[[Kaduna|HQ 1 Division]]</small>\n| marksize = 8\n| pos = right\n| bg = white\n| lat_deg = 10 | lat_min = 31\n| lon_deg = 07 | lon_min = 26\n| label2 = <small>[[Ibadan|HQ 2 Division]]</small>\n| mark2size = 8\n| pos2 = right\n| bg2 = white\n| lat2_deg = 07 | lat2_min = 23\n| lon2_deg = 03 | lon2_min = 55\n| label3 = <small>[[Jos|HQ 3 Armoured Division]]</small>\n| mark3size = 8\n| pos3 = right\n| bg3 = white\n| lat3_deg = 09 | lat3_min = 56\n| lon3_deg = 08 | lon3_min = 53\n| label4 = <small>[[Lagos|HQ 81 Division]]</small>\n| mark4 = Blue pog.svg\n| mark4size = 8\n| pos4 = right\n| bg4 = white\n| lat4_deg = 06 | lat4_min = 27\n| lon4_deg = 03 | lon4_min = 23\n| label5 = <small>[[Enugu|HQ 82 Division]]</small>\n| mark5size = 8\n| pos5 = right\n| bg5 = white\n| lat5_deg = 06 | lat5_min = 27\n| lon5_deg = 07 | lon5_min = 30\t\n| label6 = <small>[[Maiduguri|HQ 7 Division]]</small>\n| mark6size = 8\n| pos6 = right\n| bg6 = white\n| lat6_deg = 11 | lat6_min = 50\n| lon6_deg = 13 | lon6_min = 09\t\n| label7 = <small>[[Sokoto|HQ 8 Division]]</small>\n| mark7size = 8\n| pos7 = right\n| bg7 = white\n| lat7_deg = 13 | lat7_min = 04\n| lon7_deg = 5 | lon7_min = 16\n| label8 = <small>[[Port Harcourt|HQ 6 Division]]</small>\n| mark8size = 8\n| pos8 = right\n| bg8 = white\n| lat8_deg = 4 | lat8_min = 49\n| lon8_deg = 7 | lon8_min = 2\n}}\n \nThe Nigerian Army is governed by the Nigerian Army Council (NAC). The Nigerian Army is functionally organized into combat arms, which are infantry and armored; the combat support arms, which are artillery, engineers, and signals; the combat support services comprise medical, supply and transport, ordinance and finance. Others include the military police, intelligence, physical training, chaplains, public relations and band.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/nigeria/army-orbat.htm|title=Nigerian Army Order of Battle|website=www.globalsecurity.org|accessdate=16 February 2019}}</ref>\n[[Training and Doctrine Command (Nigeria)|Training and Doctrine Command]] (TRADOC) located in Minna is responsible for doctrinal, training and combat development, and supervises training centers. There are 17 Corps Training Schools and the [[Nigerian Army College of Logistics]] (NACOL).<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=\"army.mil.ng\">{{cite web|url=http://www.army.mil.ng/|title=Nigerian Army- Official Website|website=Army.mil.ng}}</ref>\n\nThe Nigerian Army said its newly created the 6th Division in Port Harcourt was established to organize and improve its internal security operations in four states of the Niger Delta. the Division will cover the Army\u2019s 2 Brigade Akwa Ibom; 16 Brigade Bayelsa and 63rd Brigade in Delta, respectively, with divisional headquarters in Port Harcourt. This arrangement will help to curtail activities of militants, banditry, inter-communal clashes, illegal bunkering, kidnapping, robberies, Niger Delta Avengers and pipeline vandalism prevalent in the area. Insecurity in these states negatively impacts on the national economy resulting from sabotage by criminal entities within the region.<ref name=\"premiumtimesng.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.premiumtimesng.com/regional/south-south-regional/215772-created-new-nigerian-army-division-niger-delta-major-general.html|title=Why we created new Nigerian Army division in Niger Delta - Major General - Premium Times Nigeria|date=19 November 2016|website=Premiumtimesng.com}}</ref>\n\nCurrent formations include:\n \n*[[1st Division (Nigeria)|1 Division]], headquartered in [[Kaduna]]<ref name=\"army.mil.ng\"/>\n*[[2 Division (Nigeria)|2 Division]] (HQ in [[Ibadan]])<ref name=\"army.mil.ng\"/>\n*[[3rd Division (Nigeria)|3 Armoured Division]] HQ in [[Jos]]<ref name=\"army.mil.ng\"/>\n*[[6th Amphibious Division]] HQ [[Port Harcourt]]<ref name=\"premiumtimesng.com\"/>\n*[[7th Infantry Division (Nigeria)|7th Infantry Division]] (OP-LD) HQ in [[Maiduguri]]<ref name=\"army.mil.ng\"/>\n*[[8th Division (Nigeria)|8th Division]] HQ [[Sokoto]]<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201611280411.html|title=Nigeria: Army Council Approves 8 Division for Sokoto|first=Ankeli|last=Emmanuel|date=28 November 2016|publisher=AllAfrica}}</ref>\n*[[81st Division (Nigeria)|81st Division]] (Amphibious) HQ in Lagos<ref name=\"army.mil.ng\"/>\n*[[82nd Division (Nigeria)|82nd Division]] (Airborne and Amphibious) HQ in [[Enugu]]<ref name=\"army.mil.ng\"/>\n*[[Training and Doctrine Command (Nigeria)|Training and Doctrine Command]] HQ [[Minna]]<ref name=\"army.mil.ng\"/>\n\nThe government and military chiefs, working with the National Assembly, civil society and international partners, need to do much more: implement comprehensive defense sector reform, including clear identification of security challenges; a new defense and security policy and structure to address them; and drastic improvement in leadership, oversight, administration and accountability across the sector.<ref name=\"crisisgroup.org\">{{cite web|url=https://www.crisisgroup.org/africa/west-africa/nigeria/nigeria-challenge-military-reform|title=Nigeria: The Challenge of Military Reform|date=6 June 2016|website=Crisisgroup.org}}</ref>\nIt currently has over 6,000 officers and 150,000 soldiers.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.janes.com/article/57231/nigerian-army-plans-to-double-in-size |title=Archived copy |access-date=13 May 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160611041920/http://www.janes.com/article/57231/nigerian-army-plans-to-double-in-size |archive-date=11 June 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Military forces abroad==\n[[File:Nigerian troops in Somalia.JPEG|thumb|right|140px|Nigerian soldiers in [[Somalia]], 1993]]\nIn December 1983 the new r\u00e9gime of the Head of State of Nigeria, Major General [[Muhammadu Buhari]], announced that Nigeria could no longer afford an activist anti-colonial role in Africa. [[English-speaking world|Anglophone]] members of the [[Economic Community of West African States]] (ECOWAS) established [[ECOMOG]], dominated by the Nigerian Army, in 1990 to intervene in the [[First Liberian Civil War|civil war in Liberia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/reports/1993/liberia/#1|title=Waging War to Keep the Peace: The ECOMOG Intervention and Human Rights (Human Rights Watch Report, June 1993)|website=Hrw.org|access-date=2017-02-06}}</ref> Smaller army forces had previously carried out UN and ECOWAS deployments in the [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|former Yugoslavia]], [[Angola]], [[Rwanda]], [[Somalia]], and [[Sierra Leone]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/nigeria/army-orbat.htm|title=Nigerian Army Order of Battle|website=www.globalsecurity.org|access-date=2019-10-27}}</ref>\n\nThe anti-colonial policy statement did not deter Nigeria under Generals [[Ibrahim Babangida]] in 1990 and [[Sani Abacha]] in 1997 from sending peacekeeping troops as part of [[ECOMOG]] under the auspices of ECOWAS into Liberia and later into [[Sierra Leone]] when civil wars broke out in those countries. President [[Olusegun Obasanjo]] in August 2003 committed Nigerian troops once again into Liberia,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.news24.com/Africa/News/Nigerian-troops-off-to-Liberia-20030719|title=Nigerian troops off to Liberia|newspaper=News24|access-date=2017-02-06}}</ref> at the urging of the United States, to provide an interim presence until the UN's force [[UNMIL]] arrived. [[Charles G. Taylor|Charles Taylor]] was subsequently eased out of power by U.S. pressure<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2003/WORLD/africa/07/09/liberia/|title=Nigeria would shield Taylor from trial|date=10 July 2003|website=CNN}}</ref> and exiled to Nigeria.\n\nIn October 2004, Nigerian troops were deployed into [[Darfur]], Sudan to spearhead an [[African Union]] force to protect civilians there.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/3562096.stm|title=BBC NEWS {{!}} Africa {{!}} Rwandan soldiers arrive in Sudan|website=news.bbc.co.uk|access-date=2017-02-06}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2013, Nigeria began to deploy troops to Mali as part of the [[African-led International Support Mission to Mali]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.vanguardngr.com/2013/01/nigeria-expends-n7bn-on-troops-logistics-to-mali-jonathan/|title=Nigeria expends N7bn on troops, logistics to Mali - Jonathan - Vanguard News|date=2013-01-30|newspaper=Vanguard News|access-date=2017-02-06|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mali-rebels-idUSBRE90M16T20130123|title=U.S., Africa say Mali action counters growing Islamist threat|date=2017-01-23|newspaper=Reuters|access-date=2017-02-06}}</ref>\n\nNigeria claimed to have contributed more than twenty thousand troops and police officers to various UN missions since 1960. The [[Nigeria Police Force]] and troops have served in places like [[UNIPOM]] (UN India-Pakistan Observer mission) 1965, [[UNIFIL]] in [[Lebanon]] 1978, the UN observer mission, [[UNIIMOG]] supervising the Iran-Iraq ceasefire in 1988, former [[Yugoslavia]] 1998, [[East Timor]] 1999, and in the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]] ([[MONUC]]) 2004.\n\nNigerian Army officers have served as [[Chief of Defence|chiefs of defence]] in other countries, with Brigadier General [[Maxwell Khobe]] serving as Sierra Leone chief of staff in 1998-1999,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dawodu.com/barrack7.htm|title=Account Suspended|website=Dawodu.com}}</ref> and Nigerian officers acting as Command Officer-in-Charge of the [[Armed Forces of Liberia]] from at least 2007.\n\n==Chiefs of the Nigerian Army==\nFollowing is a chronological list of officers holding the position of General Officer Commanding (GOC) or [[Chief of Army Staff (Nigeria)|Chief of Army Staff (COAS)]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nigerian-army.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=41&Itemid=44 |title=Archived copy |access-date=3 August 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110213012733/http://www.nigerian-army.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=41&Itemid=44 |archive-date=13 February 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"white-space: nowrap;\"\n|-\n! Officer\n! Title\n! style=\"width:12em;\"| Period Served\n! Remarks\n|-\n| Maj Gen [[Kenneth G. Exham]]\n| GOC\n| 1956\u20131959\n| [[Duke of Wellington's Regiment]]\n|-\n| Maj Gen [[Norman Foster (military officer)|Norman Foster]]\n| GOC\n| 1960\u20131962\n|\n|-\n| Maj Gen [[John Alexander Mackenzie]]\n| GOC\n| 1963\n| 2nd Battalion, [[The Lancashire Fusiliers]]\n|-\n| Maj Gen [[Christopher Welby-Everard|Sir Christopher Welby-Everard]]\n| GOC\n| 1963\u20131965\n| Last British GOC\n|-\n| Maj Gen [[Johnson Aguiyi-Ironsi]]\n| GOC\n| 1965\u20131966\n| Later military ruler\n|-\n| Lt Col [[Yakubu Gowon]] FSS\n| COAS\n| January 1966 \u2013 July 1966\n|Later military ruler\n|-\n| Lt Col [[Joseph Akahan]] OFR FSS\n| COAS\n| May 1967 \u2013 May 1968\n|\n|-\n| Maj Gen [[Hassan Katsina]] rcds psc\n| COAS\n| May 1968 \u2013 January 1971\n|\n|-\n| Maj Gen [[David Ejoor]]\n| COAS\n| January 1971 \u2013 July 1975\n|\n|-\n| Lt Gen [[Theophilus Danjuma]]\n| COAS\n| July 1975 \u2013 October 1979\n|\n|-\n| Lt Gen [[Ipoola Alani Akinrinade]] CFR FSS\n| COAS\n| October 1979 \u2013 April 1980\n| \n|-\n| Lt Gen [[Gibson Jalo]] CFR FSS JSS\n| COAS\n| April 1980 \u2013 October 1981\n|\n|-\n| Lt Gen [[Mohammed Inuwa Wushishi]] CFR FSS\n| COAS\n| October 1981 \u2013 October 1983\n|\n|-\n| Maj Gen [[Ibrahim Babangida]]\n| COAS\n| January 1984 \u2013 August 1985\n| Later military ruler\n|-\n| Lt Gen [[Sani Abacha]] GCON, DSS mni\n| COAS\n| August 1985 \u2013 August 1990\n| Last military ruler\n|-\n| Lt Gen [[Salihu Ibrahim]] FSS FHWC\n| COAS\n| August 1990 \u2013 September 1993\n|\n|-\n| Lt Gen [[Aliyu Gusau Mohammed]] DSS rcds\n| COAS\n| September 1993 \u2013 November 1993\n|\n|-\n| Maj Gen [[Chris Alli]] CRG DSS ndc psc(+)\n| COAS\n| November 1993 \u2013 August 1994??\n|\n|-\n| Maj Gen [[Alwali Kazir]] DSS Usawc psc(+)\n| COAS\n| August 1994 \u2013 March 1996\n|-\n| Lt Gen [[Ishaya Bamaiyi]] DSS Usawc psc(+)\n| COAS\n| March 1996 \u2013 May 1999\n|-\n| Lt Gen [[Victor Malu]] DSS mni fwc psc\n| COAS\n| May 1999 \u2013 April 2001\n|\n|-\n| Lt Gen [[Alexander Ogomudia]]\n| COAS\n| April 2001 \u2013 June 2003\n| Later [[Chief of the Defence Staff (Nigeria)|Chief of Defence Staff]] \n|-\n| Lt Gen [[Martin Luther Agwai]]\n| COAS\n| June 2003 \u2013 June 2006\n| Later Force Commander of the [[United Nations African Union Mission in Darfur|UNAMID]]\n|-\n| Lt Gen [[Owoye Andrew Azazi]]\n| COAS\n| 1 June 2006 \u2013 May 2007\n| Later [[Chief of the Defence Staff (Nigeria)|Chief of Defence Staff]] \n|-\n| Lt Gen [[Luka Yusuf]] \n| COAS\n| June 2007 \u2013 August 2008\n|\n|-\n| Lt Gen [[Abdulrahman Bello Dambazau]] \n| COAS\n| August 2008 \u2013 September 2010\n|\n|-\n| Lt Gen [[Azubuike Ihejirika|Onyabor Azubuike Ihejirika]] \n| COAS\n| September 2010 \u2013 January 2014\n|\n|-\n| Lt Gen [[Kenneth Minimah]] \n| COAS\n| January 2014 \u2013 July 2015\n|\n|-\n| Lt Gen [[Tukur Yusuf Buratai]] \n| COAS\n| July 2015 \u2013 Present\n| Commander [[Multinational Joint Task Force]] (May 2015 \u2013 July 2015)\n|}\n\n==Equipment==\nDespite a disproportionate emphasis on the materiel and sophistication of the Nigerian Armed Forces, and despite possessing some formidable hardware, the Army has been hamstrung by technical deficiency and an exceptionally poor standard of maintenance.<ref name=\"Fayemi\">{{cite web |url=https://kclpure.kcl.ac.uk/portal/files/2926054/321177.pdf |title=NThreats, Military Expenditure and National Security: Analysis of Trends in Nigeria's Defence Planning, 1970 - 1990 |author=John Olukayode Fayemi |publisher=University of London |accessdate=12 March 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6WytxmAg4?url=https://kclpure.kcl.ac.uk/portal/files/2926054/321177.pdf |archivedate=12 March 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Its overabundance of foreign suppliers, including [[Austria]], [[Brazil]], [[France]], [[Germany]], [[Italy]], [[Sweden]], [[Switzerland]], [[Romania]], [[Turkey]], [[Ukraine]], the former [[Soviet Union]], the [[United States]] and the [[United Kingdom]], has also complicated logistics. Calculating the size and scope of replacement inventories alone is impossible given the menagerie of equipment in use.<ref name=\"Fayemi\"/><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/11/02/world/africa/nigeria-trump-rocks.html|title=Nigerian Army Uses Trump's Words to Justify Fatal Shooting of Rock-Throwing Protesters|access-date=2018-11-04|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe Nigerian Army maintains at least eighty-two different weapon systems and 194 types of ammunition, of sixty-two different categories, from fourteen manufacturers.<ref name=\"Fayemi\"/>\n\n===Infantry weapons===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! style=\"text-align: left;\"|Name\n! style=\"width:15%;\"| Photo\n! style=\"text-align: left;\"|Type\n! style=\"text-align: left;\"|Country of Origin\n! style=\"text-align: left;\"|Notes\n|-\n! style=\"align: center; background: lavender;\" colspan=\"7\" | '''[[Handgun]]s'''\n|-\n| [[Beretta 92]]<ref name=\"diez2000\">Diez, Octavio (2000). ''Armament and Technology: Handguns''. Lema Publications, S.L. {{ISBN|84-8463-013-7}}.</ref>\n| [[File:Beretta 92 FS.gif|150px]]\n| Semi-automatic pistol\n| {{Flagu|Italy}}\n|\n|-\n| [[Beretta M1951]]<ref name=\"jones2009\">Jones, Richard D. ''Jane's Infantry Weapons 2009/2010''. Jane's Information Group; 35 edition (27 January 2009). {{ISBN|978-0-7106-2869-5}}.</ref>\n| [[File:Beretta1951.JPG|150px]]\n| Semi-Automatic pistol \n| {{Flagu|Italy}}\n|\n|-\n| [[Browning Hi-Power]]\n| [[File:Flickr - ~Steve Z~ - 1971 Browning Hi Power 10.jpg|150px]]\n| Semi-Automatic Pistol\n| {{Flagu|Belgium}} {{Flagu|Nigeria}}\n| Some of Nigerian manufacture, designated NP-1.<ref>[http://www.dicon.gov.ng/military1.html Defense Industries Corporation of Nigeria] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131227081924/http://www.dicon.gov.ng/military1.html |date=27 December 2013 }} Retrieved on 1 May 2013.</ref>\n|-\n| [[Walther P5]]<ref name=\"diez2000\"/>\n| [[File:Waltherp5.jpg|150px]]\n| Semi-Automatic Pistol \n| {{Flagu|West Germany}}\n|\n|-\n! style=\"align: center; background: lavender;\" colspan=\"7\" | '''[[Submachine gun]]s'''\n|-\n| [[Beretta M12]]<ref name = \"Gander\">{{cite book|last = Gander| first = Jerry| title = Jane's Infantry Weapons 2002-2003 | publisher = Jane's Information Group| year = 2002| isbn =0-7106-2434-4 | pages =214, 899\u2013906}}</ref>\n| [[File:Beretta M12.jpg|150px]]\n| Submachine gun \n| {{Flagu|Italy}} {{Flagu|Nigeria}}\n| Some of Nigerian manufacture.<ref name=\"dicon.gov.ng\">[http://www.dicon.go